ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-2 Any errors in this report will be corrected when the final report has been completed. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-3 On September 25, 2000, at 1700 hours Pacific daylight time, a Culver LFA, N37820, ran off the runway, and nosed over while landing on a private airstrip near Ione, California. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-4 The airplane was destroyed, and the certificated airline transport pilot received serious injuries. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-5 The airplane was owned and operated by the pilot as a personal flight under 14 CFR Part 91 when the accident occurred. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-6 The local flight originated from the private airstrip earlier that afternoon. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-7 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed at the time, and no flight plan was filed. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-8 A witness reported that the pilot was landing to the east on the east-west dirt strip when the airplane began veering to the right. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-9 After rolling about 300 feet down the strip, the airplane ran off the right side of the runway, struck a fence collapsing the main gear, and nosed over. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-10 The witness also reported that after looking at the airplane's track in the dirt, it appeared that the right main was more pronounced. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-11 He said that the right main tire also showed evidence of abrasion on its tread surface. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-12 He checked the brakes in the airplane and found that the right brake was "definitely" dragging. 
ntsb3950txt-1-5-5-0-13 He reported that the airplane was equipped with Cleveland brakes in accordance with the applicable supplemental type certificate (STC). 
